283
00:12:51,660 --> 00:12:53,560
In this module,
we have talked about

284
00:12:53,560 --> 00:12:55,960
how sanitation services are organized

285
00:12:56,510 --> 00:12:58,270
and how they
can be financed.

286
00:12:59,170 --> 00:13:01,600
Key take-away messages
are as follows:

287
00:13:02,450 --> 00:13:04,250
One size does not fit all;

288
00:13:04,860 --> 00:13:06,160
there are many different ways

289
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:08,760
to organize the delivery
of sanitation services.

290
00:13:09,740 --> 00:13:12,130
A key principle
would be to maintain

291
00:13:12,130 --> 00:13:14,140
a separation
between policy,

292
00:13:14,140 --> 00:13:17,340
regulation and service
provision functions,

293
00:13:17,340 --> 00:13:20,110
so as to ensure
checks and balances.

294
00:13:21,580 --> 00:13:23,840
Sanitation services
can be provided

295
00:13:23,840 --> 00:13:26,480
by public or private
service providers.

296
00:13:27,480 --> 00:13:29,940
Bringing in the private sector requires

297
00:13:29,940 --> 00:13:32,630
clear regulatory arrangements,

298
00:13:32,630 --> 00:13:36,070
via licenses or contracts
for service provision.

299
00:13:37,570 --> 00:13:39,750
Sanitation services
can be funded

300
00:13:39,750 --> 00:13:41,600
from a variety of sources.

301
00:13:42,210 --> 00:13:44,080
However, public funds

302
00:13:44,080 --> 00:13:46,230
need to be spent
in a smarter

303
00:13:46,230 --> 00:13:47,900
and more catalytic manner,

304
00:13:48,440 --> 00:13:50,120
to ensure that
the Sustainable

305
00:13:50,120 --> 00:13:52,320
Development Goal
of universal access

306
00:13:52,320 --> 00:13:55,330
to sanitation becomes a reality.

